  Where the LLM Fits

  The DSL you've designed is intentional structure - it requires users to speak in a vocabulary that maps to domains. But here's where the LLM can bridge the gap:

  Current Flow:
  User speaks → Transcription → Raw text → Manual @context tags → Parser

  LLM-Enhanced Flow:
  User speaks → Transcription → LLM understands intent → Suggests/inserts @context tags → Parser

  The LLM becomes a "DSL Translator":
  - User says: "I need to remember to call my mom tomorrow"
  - LLM recognizes: This is a task with a due date
  - LLM outputs: - [ ] Call mom @context(task) @when(2025-11-28)

  The LLM becomes a "Domain Recognizer":
  - User says: "I've decided to focus on yoga for the next 3 months"
  - LLM recognizes: This is a choice (decision) that leads to goals
  - LLM outputs: - [ ] Focus on yoga @context(choice) @link(goal:health/yoga-practice)

